                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t16961014-14-off79 t16961014-14-cd80"></join> last. It appeared by the Evidence, That they did see him Coyning and Casting of Shillings, Six-pences, and Half-Crowns, at one Hicks's House in <placeName id="t16961014-14-crimeloc81">Shadwell</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t16961014-14-crimeloc81" type="placeName" value="Shadwell"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t16961014-14-crimeloc81" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t16961014-14-off79 t16961014-14-crimeloc81"></join>, and that the little Half-Crowns were designed to be got into the Exchequer, and that he did sell the false Six-pences for 2 d. apiece, that they were made of a sort of Metal called Spelter, that he had made above 50 l. of that Money. He denied the Fact, but confess'd that he had been at Hicks's House several times, and that he did use to hold the Flasks for Hicks when he poured in the Metal, and said Hicks told him that they were Drops for Cabinets which he did Cast, but did not know what they were; it did not avail him. The Jury found him <rs id="t16961014-14-verdict82" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16961014-14-verdict82" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               Guilty
            </rs> of High-Treason.</p>
